# Chinese Past-Time Grammar Compared to Polish

## Key Difference (Overview)

- **Chinese** has **no grammatical past tense**.
  Past meaning is expressed using **aspect markers**, **time words**, or **context**.
- **Polish** uses **past tense verb conjugation**, which agrees with **gender and number**.

---

## 1. Completed Action — 了 (le)

### Chinese
我吃了饭。

### Polish
Zjadłem obiad. / Zjadłam obiad.

### Word-by-word (Gloss)
- 我 (wǒ) — I  
- 吃 (chī) — eat  
- 了 (le) — aspect marker (completed action)  
- 饭 (fàn) — meal / rice  

### English
I ate a meal.

### Grammar Note
- **了** marks that the action is **completed**, not that it is grammatically “past”.
- Polish expresses past by changing the verb form (**zjadłem / zjadłam**).

---

## 2. Past Experience — 过 (guò)

### Chinese
我去过中国。

### Polish
Byłem w Chinach. / Byłam w Chinach.

### Word-by-word (Gloss)
- 我 (wǒ) — I  
- 去 (qù) — go  
- 过 (guò) — experiential aspect (have ever done)  
- 中国 (Zhōngguó) — China  

### English
I have been to China.

### Grammar Note
- **过** means the action happened **at least once in the past**, experience-focused.
- Polish past tense simply states the fact.

---

## 3. Past State (No Marker Needed)

### Chinese
昨天我很忙。

### Polish
Wczoraj byłem zajęty. / Byłam zajęta.

### Word-by-word (Gloss)
- 昨天 (zuótiān) — yesterday  
- 我 (wǒ) — I  
- 很 (hěn) — very  
- 忙 (máng) — busy  

### English
Yesterday I was very busy.

### Grammar Note
- Time word **昨天 (yesterday)** is enough to indicate past.
- No verb change or aspect marker in Chinese.
- Polish uses past tense of **być**.

---

## 4. Past Ongoing Action — 正在 / 在

### Chinese
我来的时候，他正在睡觉。

### Polish
Kiedy przyszedłem, on spał.

### Word-by-word (Gloss)
- 我 (wǒ) — I  
- 来的 (lái de) — came (relative clause)  
- 时候 (shíhou) — when / time  
- 他 (tā) — he  
- 正在 (zhèngzài) — right now (progressive marker)  
- 睡觉 (shuìjiào) — sleep  

### English
When I arrived, he was sleeping.

### Grammar Note
- Chinese uses **正在 / 在** for ongoing action.
- Polish expresses this with **imperfective past verb**.

---

## 5. Past Negative — 没（有）

### Chinese
我昨天没去工作。

### Polish
Wczoraj nie poszedłem do pracy. / Nie poszłam do pracy.

### Word-by-word (Gloss)
- 我 (wǒ) — I  
- 昨天 (zuótiān) — yesterday  
- 没 (méi) — did not  
- 去 (qù) — go  
- 工作 (gōngzuò) — work  

### English
I didn’t go to work yesterday.

### Grammar Note
- **没**, not **不**, is used for **past negation**.
- Polish again relies on verb conjugation.

---

## 6. “Already” in the Past — 已经 (yǐjīng)

### Chinese
我已经做完了作业。

### Polish
Już skończyłem pracę domową. / Już skończyłam pracę domową.

### Word-by-word (Gloss)
- 我 (wǒ) — I  
- 已经 (yǐjīng) — already  
- 做完 (zuò wán) — finish doing  
- 了 (le) — completion marker  
- 作业 (zuòyè) — homework  

### English
I have already finished my homework.

### Grammar Note
- Chinese stacks **time adverb + result + 了**.
- Polish uses **już** + past tense.

---

## Summary Table (Conceptual)

- Chinese: **aspect + time words + context**
- Polish: **past tense verb morphology**
- Chinese verbs **never change form**
- Polish verbs **must change** (gender, number)
